description.narrative:
The initiative includes support for the World Bank's "Umbrella Trust Fund on Jobs" (UTF Jobs) 2015-2017 of a total of SEK 60 million. The World Bank has two overarching goals by 2030: (1) to eradicate extreme poverty by reducing the proportion of people living on less than $ 1.25 per day to a maximum of 3%; (2) to contribute to the prosperity of all by promoting income and economic growth for the poorest 40% in each country.

The overall goal of UTF Jobs is to support the design and implementation of the World Bank's employment strategy. This strategy aims to improve the conditions for productive jobs for workers worldwide, help eradicate poverty and increase common prosperity. This requires integrated tools and solutions that make it easier for the private sector to create new jobs, to increase the productivity of existing jobs and to support individuals - including young people and women - in finding a job.

The goals of the contribution are:
1) to develop employment data and diagnostic tools;
2) to conduct research and so-called "Impact evaluations" for identified employment challenges (e.g. job creation in conflict countries and short-term compromises between productivity growth and job creation);
3) to design integrated employment strategies in different country contexts and in partnership with the private sector;
4) to support countries in the introduction of innovative solutions for job creation through advice, coordination and financial services;
5) to help build the capacity of the World Bank's customers to collect and analyze data and models, and to implement diagnostic tools, strategies and programs - in order to build accountability and sustainability; and
6) to develop partnerships between practitioners in the field and the private sector - to influence the design and support the implementation of the above measures.

Sida believes that the fund's goals are well in line with current strategies and policy frameworks. GECO has for a long time wanted to supplement its portfolio on employment issues and it is judged that this effort complements the global support for the International Labor Organization (ILO) and WIEGO (Women in Informal Employment: Globalizing and Organizing). At present, no further support is planned in the area. The assessment is that Sida with this support has a good coverage of employment issues globally, and that the fund is well connected to bilateral and regional initiatives in the area.

The added value of supporting the World Bank, in relation to the above-mentioned support, is its experience of working with large-scale market programs as well as with the private sector. The bank has a clearer focus on the demand side of the labor market than, for example, the ILO. The World Bank also has a clearer mandate to work with the informal sector on an overall level, in relation to the ILO, which is more tied to the so-called "decent work" agenda.
